      A man from Texas set a Guinness World Record for holding  urlLink nine snakes in his mouth  for 10 seconds. This beat the previous record of eight snakes. Of course, he held that record, too. And he plans on besting this record. Why keep doing it? If you're convinced you can do 12 snakes, why mess around with 8, 9, or 10? Do it once a be done, pal! Jackie "The Snakeman" Bibby has done TV appearances and the like to make money off this stunt, but was not paid for this record-breaking acheivement. In what may be my favorite line in the article, he did it "for the prestige, the glory and the attention." Yes, the glory of holding nine rattlesnakes in your mouth. One big question I have is, how do you come to find out you're capable of doing this? This is the way I imagine it: You are out camping with your friends, drunk beyond belief, when one says "Hey! I bet you can't put that rattlesnake in your mouth!" So, of course you prove  him wrong. You see the "prestige" holding a poisonous reptile in your mouth garners among your circle of friends, then decide to practice and improve so that one day EVERYONE will see the "glory" in your actions as you hold nine of them in your mouth and break your own world record. It's a life only a chosen few can aspire to lead. 
    
