      Last night I was getting into my car, and the driver's side seat is covered with these chunks of ice, all on the back and seat. I look on the driver's side window, also covered with ice on the inside. "What?!" I'm thinking. I check to make sure the window is rolled all the way up. It is. Then I find the culprit. In the cupholder. My can of Diet Dr. Pepper (Thanks, Jill!) from the night before had exploded and then froze in its explosion pattern. One point for exploding pop. Well, I'm late for my destination, so I say, "No time to clean this off!" and I just get a blanket from the backseat and sit on it. I'm just driving across town, no big deal. The windshield has a little frost on it, but I figure it's nothing that will prevent me from driving the 2 miles I'm going. I'm not even halfway across the parking lot, when I realize, I can't see. So I stop in the middle of the parking lot (it's empty) to scrape my windshield. I also try the trick that I seem to always try, but I don't remember it ever working. Windshield wiper fluid. Maybe this works in Missouri when it's around 30, but it doesn't work in ND when it's -3. But, I kept driving, with the windshield wipers going and the fluid still refreezing on the outside. Also, I'm getting a thin lair of frost inside. I pull onto the street, then freak because I can't see at all. So I just stop. I would have pulled over, but I couldn't tell if there were parked cars or not. After sitting in the street for about 30 seconds and trying the wiper fluid trick again, I rolled down my window and did my best Ace Ventura impersonation so that I could drive the 20  yards to the parking lot up ahead. One point for making me stick my head out of my car in -3 degree weather.  (Side note, not related to weather. When I finally got to my destination, the people I was meeting weren't there. I was at the wrong bar. When I finally met them, it was 25 minutes after I left my apartment. It should have taken 5-10 minutes to get there. Grrr.) And the final point is for this being one of the first things I heard this morning, which prevented me from leaving my warm covers which resulted in me being late to work: "Current temperature, 12 below."
    
