      Everytime I mentioned the Montana trip to my mom, she would sing the above line. I think she made up the song, but she swears it's real. Anyway, some things from the Montana trip... -- I've never been happier to be short than while riding on the NDSCS bus. I sat across the aisle from one of our 6'7" guards, and he did not look comfortable at all the entire trip. It was a little hazardous sitting across from him, too, because he stretched out across the aisle and had his feet on the armrest on the outside chair in my row (I was sitting by the window) while he was taking a nap. Occasionally, and I do this while I nap, too, he would move suddenly. I got kicked twice.  -- After getting kicked  couple times, I stretched out my legs to see if they even reached across the aisle. Not even close. --We stopped at a gas station in western North Dakota on the way out. There was a "For Sale" ad posted on the bulletin board with a picture of the item for sale. The picture looked like a tree stump. Huh? Who buys a tree stump? -- I feel confident the crowd at the Miles City game had the highest number of cowboy hats per capita of anyplace I've ever been. And my 6th grade field trip was to a rodeo. -- Not to be outdone by the fans in Miles City, the Dawson CC women's coach "cowboyed up," wearing a turquoise-studded, giant belt buckle. Never again will I complain about one of Quin's outfits. -- We have a player on the women's team from Watertown, S.D. -- the hometown of one Jason Sutherland. Her parents came to the game, and we talked about old number five, how scrappy he was, how he got a lot of T's, how it wasn't HIS fault Tyus Edny broke the hearts of every Tiger fan... it was good fun. They said their HS gym, which holds 4,000, would be full at 4:00 when he played at 7:00. Man, I love that guy! -- Before loading the bus on Sunday morning, I was watching Fox News in the hotel lobby, and some of the men's team were eating breakfast. As I surveyed the people in the room, it hit me, I was the ONLY American there. I was surrounded by Canadians. They kept yapping about how the American media always spins it so the USA is the hero, and so on and so forth. One guy even said, "Just be the bad guy, for once!" It was a very strange experience, watching a major world event surrounded by people with a totally different perspective. -- When I still wanted to work in TV, one of my biggest fear was ending up in Glendive, Mont., the smallest media market in the USA. I was sure that if I worked there, I'd have to run a crank to get the tower working. Well, I faced my former fear this weekend when I visited Glendive, home of Dawson Community College. Let me tell you, my fears were rational. The Wahp's no hot spot, but Glendive...yikes. -- Here's a question. What do you do when your printer gets a paper jam? You unjam it, right? Well, the women's coaches disagree, and they would not let me use "unjam" in our on-bus scrabble game. Grrrr. -- This weekend was good for my morale. I realized that if I decide to make this my career path, I would be doing more of the things I did this weekend, and less pretending to be busy in my office. I really had a lot of fun with the teams. It was fun to finally see the personalities of some of the players. They're a fun bunch of kids. I like them so much, in fact, that if I get really excited during the Great Bake-O-Rama scheduled for Tuesday and Wednesday, I might just make them all cookies for their next road trip. -- Speaking of cookies, the parents I mentioned before were so nice. The mom made me give her my address here, because "Maybe I'll feel like sending you a care package or something. It's just the Mom in me!" Whoo hooo! Potential cookies!!! -- Miles had programs that I'm assuming were sponsored by Pepsi, as they had three large Pepsi logos on the inside. Along the bottom of the page were pictures of officials and explanations of what officials' signals mean. For example, they showed a guy with his hands on his hips, and below it said "Blocking." The last signal had a guy with his hand over his head, and below him it said "Have a Pepsi." Of all the years I've spent involved in the sport of basketball, I never knew "Have a Pepsi" had an official signal... 
    
</post>

